  <title>Basic features</title>

  <p>"Drawing" is a basic drawing application for the GNOME desktop, which can
  edit or create pictures (PNG, JPEG or BMP).</p>
  <p>Basic features are located in the header of the window, such as the
  <gui style="button">Open</gui> menu, the <gui style="button">Save</gui>
  button, and the primary menu.</p>
  <p>The primary menu allows you to:</p>

  <list>
    <item>
      <p>Print the picture.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>See the pictures properties, such as its size and colorspace.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Export the image or save it as a new file. Both options don't overwrite
      the original file. With <gui style="menuitem">Export as…</gui>, you keep
      editing the original file, but <gui style="menuitem">Save as…</gui> closes
      the original file and makes you edit the new one.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Show tools names. Edit <link xref="preferences">preferences</link>.</p>
    </item>
  </list>

  <media type="image" mime="image/png" width="450"
  src="figures/screenshot_menu.png" its:translate="no"/>

  <p>The <gui style="button">Open</gui> menu is merged in the primary menu if
  the window size is too small to display its button. With <link xref="preferences">
  the elementaryOS layout</link>, this menu is partly replaced by buttons.</p>

  <list>
    <item>
      <p>Open a new window.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Open a new image. It can be a blank image, or an image created from the
      clipboard content, or an image created from the current selection.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Open a picture file.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Import a picture into the currently edited one.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Paste a picture into the currently edited one.</p>
    </item>
  </list>

  <p>You can edit the opened picture with the <link xref="drawing_tools">tools
  </link> in the side bar. The <gui style="button">Undo</gui> and
  <gui style="button">Redo</gui> buttons are located in the header of the
  window.</p>

  <p>In the bottom bar, the <gui style="button">Preview</gui> button (not
  available with <link xref="selection_canvas">some tools</link>) displays a
  thumbnail of the full picture you're editing.</p>

